## Phase 1 — Write-Ahead Logging (WAL) for Crash Recovery

> **Resume bullet:** *"Implemented Write-Ahead Logging (WAL) to guarantee ACID Durability — the engine logs all mutations to a sequential append-only journal before applying them, enabling crash recovery on restart."*

### What it is and why it matters

Real databases (PostgreSQL, SQLite, MySQL) never write directly to their primary data files. If the process crashes mid-write, the file becomes corrupted. Instead, every mutation (`INSERT`, `UPDATE`, `DELETE`) is first appended to a sequential log file called the **Write-Ahead Log**. Only after this append is confirmed does the engine apply the change to the data files.

On startup, the engine **replays** the WAL to recover uncommitted or partially-applied operations. This is what makes databases crash-safe — a core property of the "D" in **ACID**.

### Design

```
SQL Command
     │
     ▼
  Executor
     │
     ├──➤ 1. Append to wal.log  ◀── flush to disk (fsync)
     │
     └──➤ 2. Apply to data file
```

```
data/
  ├── employees.csv       ← primary data file
  ├── wal.log             ← sequential journal (one entry per mutation)
  └── wal.log.checkpoint  ← tracks how far the WAL has been applied
```

### WAL Log Entry Format (per line)
```
LSN|TIMESTAMP|TABLE|OPERATION|DATA
1  |1712004000|employees|INSERT|Alice,30
2  |1712004001|cities|INSERT|Delhi,12000000
```
- **LSN (Log Sequence Number):** A monotonically increasing integer that uniquely identifies every operation in the log.
- On startup, the engine reads `wal.log`, finds the last successfully-applied LSN from the checkpoint, and re-applies any entries after it.

### New Files to Create

| File | Role |
|---|---|
| `engine/WalManager.java` | Handles all WAL append, flush, and replay logic |
| `engine/WalEntry.java` | Data class for a single log record |
| `data/wal.log` | The journal file (auto-created) |

### Modified Files

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `engine/StorageEngine.java` | `insertRow()` calls `WalManager.append()` before writing |
| `engine/Executor.java` | On `CREATE TABLE`, log the schema definition to WAL |
| `Main.java` | On startup, call `WalManager.recover()` before entering REPL |

### Key Interview Talking Points
- Explain the difference between **physical logging** (logging raw bytes) vs. **logical logging** (logging SQL statements) — your WAL uses logical logging.
- Explain **fsync** and why a database must force the OS to flush its buffer to disk, not just call `write()`.
- Explain **checkpointing**: periodically copying WAL-applied state to the main file and truncating the WAL so it doesn't grow forever.

