## Phase 2 — Custom Binary Storage Format

> **Resume bullet:** *"Replaced text-based CSV storage with a custom binary page-structured file format, reducing read/write overhead and enabling proper typed storage with byte-level data packing."*

### What it is and why it matters

CSV is a text format — everything is stored as human-readable strings. This means even storing the integer `42` costs 2 bytes as text, and you must parse it on every read. More critically, CSV can't store data of variable lengths efficiently because there's no length-prefix metadata.

Real databases store data in **fixed-size pages** (typically 4KB or 8KB). Each page contains a header and a series of packed records. Reading a page is a single disk I/O operation. This is the single most important architectural decision in database internals.

### File Layout Design

```
customers.db
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐  Offset 0
│           FILE HEADER (128 bytes)   │
│  magic: 0xC0RE (4 bytes)            │
│  version: 1 (2 bytes)               │
│  page_size: 4096 (4 bytes)          │
│  num_columns: N (2 bytes)           │
│  schema block: name:type repeating  │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤  Offset 128
│              PAGE 0                 │  4096 bytes
│  page_header (16 bytes)             │
│    page_id, num_slots, free_space   │
│  slot_directory (variable)          │
│    [offset_to_row_1, len_row_1]     │
│    [offset_to_row_2, len_row_2]     │
│  ─ ─ ─ ─ free space ─ ─ ─ ─ ─     │
│  row_N: [INT:4bytes][STR_LEN:2][str]│
│  row_1: [INT:4bytes][STR_LEN:2][str]│
├─────────────────────────────────────┤  Offset 4224
│              PAGE 1                 │
│  ...                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Row Encoding by Type

| SQL Type | Binary Representation | Bytes |
|---|---|---|
| `INT` / `INTEGER` | Raw 4-byte signed int (big-endian) | 4 |
| `STRING` | 2-byte length prefix + UTF-8 bytes | 2 + N |
| `BOOLEAN` *(future)* | 1 byte (0 or 1) | 1 |

### Page Manager Design

A **BufferPool** is introduced — an in-memory cache of pages. This prevents re-reading the same page from disk on every query.

```
Query ──▶ Executor ──▶ BufferPool ──▶ (cache miss) ──▶ Disk
                            │
                     (cache hit)
                            │
                            ▼
                         Page (in-memory)
```

### New Files to Create

| File | Role |
|---|---|
| `engine/PageManager.java` | Reads/writes 4KB pages from `.db` files |
| `engine/BufferPool.java` | In-memory LRU cache of recently-used pages |
| `engine/BinaryStorageEngine.java` | Replaces `StorageEngine.java`, implements the paged format |
| `engine/RowSerializer.java` | Encodes/decodes a row `List<String>` to/from binary |

### Migration Strategy
- Both engines exist simultaneously.
- A `--storage=binary` flag picks the engine. Default stays CSV for backward compatibility.
- A `migrate` CLI command converts existing CSV tables to `.db` format.

