## Phase 3 — B-Tree Indexing

> **Resume bullet:** *"Designed and implemented a B-Tree index structure on primary key columns, reducing point-query complexity from O(N) full-table scan to O(log N) tree traversal, mirroring how PostgreSQL implements its default index type."*

### What it is and why it matters

A full-table scan (`SELECT ... WHERE id = 42`) loads every page from disk and checks every row. With 1 million rows, this is catastrophically slow. An **index** is a separate data structure that maps column values to their byte offset (or page ID + slot) in the data file.

A **B-Tree** (balanced tree) is the universal choice for database indexing because it:
- Supports point queries: `WHERE id = 42` → O(log N)  
- Supports range queries: `WHERE id > 100 AND id < 500` → O(log N + K)
- Stays balanced regardless of insertion order

### B-Tree Node Structure

```
                    [25, 50]                   ← Root (internal node)
                  /     |     \
          [10,15]     [30,40]     [60,75]      ← Internal nodes
          /   |  \
    [5,7] [12] [17,20]                         ← Leaf nodes (hold actual data pointers)
```

Each **leaf node** stores: `{ key (INT) → page_id, slot_id }`  
Each **internal node** stores: `{ key, left_child_ptr, right_child_ptr }`

### SQL Surface

```sql
-- Create an index
CREATE INDEX idx_employees_id ON employees(id);

-- Your SELECT automatically uses the index (no syntax change needed)
SELECT * FROM employees WHERE id = 42;

-- Explain the query plan  
EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM employees WHERE id = 42;
-- Output: "Index Scan using idx_employees_id on employees (cost=0.29)"
```

### New Files to Create

| File | Role |
|---|---|
| `index/BTreeNode.java` | Represents a single B-Tree node (internal or leaf) |
| `index/BTree.java` | Core B-Tree with `insert(key, rowPtr)`, `search(key)`, `rangeSearch(lo, hi)` |
| `index/IndexManager.java` | Manages the lifecycle of all indexes; persists index to disk as `.idx` files |
| `ast/CreateIndexQuery.java` | New AST node for `CREATE INDEX` |
| `parser/Parser.java` | Updated to parse `CREATE INDEX` and `EXPLAIN` |

### Index File on Disk

```
tables/
  employees.db        ← data file
  employees.idx       ← B-Tree index serialized to disk
```

